Introduction

This is a data sets that compares the SAT scores of all the States and Washington DC along with the amount these states invest into their public education system. I got this data set from checking the R data sets for interesting data. I wanted to analyze this data because education is an important part of a healthy democracy, and I want to analyze where we should invest to get the most benefits. This dataset has 6 numerical variables which are pop(The Population of the state in 1000s), SATV(The average verbal SAT score of the high schooler in the state), SATM(The average math SAT score of the high school students in the state), percent(the percentage of highs school student who took the SAT exam in the state), dollars (State spending on public education in 1000 dollars per student), and the pay (THe average teachers salary in the state in $1000s). There is also the categorical data region, which states the states name. We will add an additional variable called Rich which will be true if the state spends more than the median on thier public education(the dollars variable). There are naturally 51 observation as there are 50 states and 1 Washington DC. We expect there to be around half of the 51 variables to be Rich since that is how medians work.

library(tidyverse)
library(carData)
# read your datasets in here, e.g., with read_csv()
data("States")

# if your dataset needs tidying, do so here we use the amount
# the state spent on public education to determine if that
# region is rich or not.
St <- States %>% mutate(Rich = case_when(dollars > median(States$dollars) ~ 
    TRUE, TRUE ~ FALSE))

St %>% group_by(Rich) %>% count()
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
## # Groups:   Rich [2]
##   Rich      n
##   <lgl> <int>
## 1 FALSE    26
## 2 TRUE     25

Cluster Analysis

library(cluster)
library(GGally)
# clustering code here
Stnum <- St %>% select(is.numeric)



sil_width <- vector()  #empty vector to hold mean sil width
for (i in 2:10) {
    kms <- kmeans(Stnum, centers = i)  #compute k-means solution for each k
    sil <- silhouette(kms$cluster, dist(Stnum))  #get sil widths
    sil_width[i] <- mean(sil[, 3])  #take averages (higher is better)
}
ggplot() + geom_line(aes(x = 1:10, y = sil_width)) + scale_x_continuous(name = "k", 
    breaks = 1:10)  #it seems k=2 is the best cluster choice.

St_pam <- Stnum %>% pam(k = 2)

St_pam$silinfo$avg.width  #overall average silhouette width
## [1] 0.7132683
St %>% mutate(cluster = as.factor(St_pam$clustering)) %>% ggpairs(cols = 1:8, 
    aes(color = cluster))

As we can see from the graph of silhouette width over k, the k with the highest silhouette width is 2. We used pam(k=2) on our dataset, and had a silhouette width of 0.7132683, which means the cluster is a very good fit. We didnt use gower similarities to assign the clusters since that resulted in a poor fit of arund 0.4-0.5 range which was worse than what we have here. From the pairwise combination of variables graphs, we see that the clusters are most separated on population size, while everything else usually overlaps. The red cluster seems to be the states with the lowest populations, which seems to generally have higher verbal and math SAT scores, lower percentage of students taking the SAT, lower dollars invested in public education and lower pay for their teachers on average. There would be less demand for teachers in a less populated area which would mean lower pay for teachers. The amount of dollars per student invested into education is probably the values that overlap the most, which suggests that most states have similar amount of dollars per student invested into education; although, the slight increase in average dollars spent by the blue clusters doesnt seem to provide good results as all the test scores dont seem to follow. The fact that states with lower population seemed to have higher SAT scores is interesting. The fact that states where they had higher verbal and math SAT s cores were the states with a lower percentage of the student participating is also interesting.

Dimensionality Reduction with PCA

# PCA code here
pca1 <- princomp(Stnum, cor = T)
pca1$sdev/2  #this shows the amount of variation covered by each principal component
##     Comp.1     Comp.2     Comp.3     Comp.4     Comp.5     Comp.6 
## 0.98869661 0.48386423 0.47198086 0.18476803 0.15503776 0.08609622
pca1$scores %>% as.data.frame() %>% ggplot(aes(x = Comp.1, y = Comp.2)) + 
    geom_point()

The principle component score for the principle component is two times the amount of variance explained by the principle component; therefore, a higher pc score means that the component explained a lot of the variations in the original data. We see that the principle component 1 explains 0.989 or 98.9% of the variance, while the principle component 2 explains 0.484 or 48.4% of the variance. The plot of the principle component 2 vs principle component 1 looks flat with little variations around y=0 line of the graph, which is due to the fact that principle component 1 which explains a lot of the variance is now the x axis.

Linear Classifier

# linear classifier code here for this part it was said that
# we can remove some columns in the announcement.
St2 <- St %>% select(!pop & !dollars)
logistic_fit <- glm(Rich ~ ., data = St2, family = "binomial")

prob_reg <- predict(logistic_fit, type = "response")
class_diag(prob_reg, truth = St$Rich, positive = "TRUE")
##           acc sens   spec    ppv     f1     ba    auc
## Metrics 0.902 0.84 0.9615 0.9545 0.8936 0.9008 0.9615
pred <- factor(prob_reg > 0.5, levels = c("TRUE", "FALSE"))
truth <- factor(St$Rich == "TRUE", levels = c("TRUE", "FALSE"))
table(actual = truth, predicted = pred) %>% addmargins()  #confusion matrix
##        predicted
## actual  TRUE FALSE Sum
##   TRUE    21     4  25
##   FALSE    1    25  26
##   Sum     22    29  51
# cross-validation of linear classifier here
set.seed(320)
k = 10

data <- sample_frac(St2)  #randomly order rows
folds <- rep(1:k, length.out = nrow(data))  #create folds

diags <- NULL

i = 1
for (i in 1:k) {
    # create training and test sets
    train <- data[folds != i, ]
    test <- data[folds == i, ]
    truth <- test$Rich
    
    # train model
    fit <- glm(Rich ~ ., data = train, family = "binomial")
    
    
    # test model
    probs <- predict(fit, newdata = test, type = "response")  ### GET PREDICTIONS FROM THE TRAINED MODEL ON THE TEST SET HERE
    pred <- factor(probs > 0.5, levels = c("TRUE", "FALSE"))
    truth <- factor(truth == "TRUE", levels = c("TRUE", "FALSE"))
    # get performance metrics for each fold
    diags <- rbind(diags, class_diag(probs, truth = truth, positive = "TRUE"))
}

# average performance metrics across all folds
summarize_all(diags, mean)
##    acc sens  spec  ppv      f1     ba  auc
## 1 0.84 0.85 0.875 0.85 0.82001 0.8625 0.95

It seems that our logistic regression fit was extremely effective on our modified data as the AUC is 0.9615 which makes it great as the AUC essentially measure the sensitivity and specificity of the data and an AUC close to one means that the model accurately predicted both the true positive and negatives. From our confusion matrix we also see that the sensitivity was 21/25, which means it correctly identified 21 out of the 25 rich states while the specificity was, 25/26, which means that it correctly identified 25 our of the 26 non rich states. This naturally explains the high AUC. It seems that our average AUC over the CVs is 0.95 which is slightly less than our previous AUC of 0.9615, which suggests some slight overfitting which just means that the model is slightly better at predicting under the model it trained rather than new data sets; however, it would still be considered great.

Non-Parametric Classifier

library(caret)
# non-parametric classifier code here
knn_fit <- knn3(Rich ~ ., data = St2)

# your code here
prob_knn <- predict(knn_fit, St2)

class_diag(prob_knn[, 2], truth = St2$Rich, positive = "TRUE")
##            acc sens   spec    ppv     f1     ba  auc
## Metrics 0.8235  0.8 0.8462 0.8333 0.8163 0.8231 0.92
pred <- factor(prob_knn[, 2] > 0.5, levels = c("TRUE", "FALSE"))
truth <- factor(St$Rich == "TRUE", levels = c("TRUE", "FALSE"))

table(actual = truth, predicted = pred) %>% addmargins()  #confusion matrix
##        predicted
## actual  TRUE FALSE Sum
##   TRUE    20     5  25
##   FALSE    4    22  26
##   Sum     24    27  51
# cross-validation of np classifier here
set.seed(320)
k = 10

data <- sample_frac(St2)  #randomly order rows
folds <- rep(1:k, length.out = nrow(data))  #create folds

diags <- NULL

i = 1
for (i in 1:k) {
    # create training and test sets
    train <- data[folds != i, ]
    test <- data[folds == i, ]
    truth <- test$Rich
    
    # train model
    knn_fit <- knn3(Rich ~ ., data = train)
    
    # test model
    probs <- predict(knn_fit, newdata = test)
    
    # get performance metrics for each fold
    diags <- rbind(diags, class_diag(probs[, 2], truth, positive = "TRUE"))
}

# average performance metrics across all folds
summarize_all(diags, mean)
##    acc    sens  spec     ppv  f1      ba     auc
## 1 0.67 0.59167 0.725 0.63333 NaN 0.65833 0.86666

This shows an auc of 0.92 which would be considered great. From the confussion matrix, we see that the sensitivity is 20/25 and the specificity is 22/26 which means it correctly identified 20 out of the 25 rich states, while correctly identifying 22 out of 26 non-rich state. This show that we now have an average AUc of 0.904 which is less than what we had before of 0.92 which suggest overfitting; however this AUC is still greater than 0.90 which means it is great. In terms of cross validataion performance, our logistic regression fit is still better as it has an AUC of 0.95.

Regression/Numeric Prediction

# regression model code here
fit <- train(SATM ~ pay + percent, data = St2, method = "rpart")

y_pred = predict(fit)

mean((St$SATM - y_pred)^2)  #the mean square error of the overall dataset
## [1] 249.9671
# cross-validation of regression model here
cv <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10, classProbs = T, 
    savePredictions = T)
fit <- train(SATM ~ pay + percent, data = St2, trControl = cv, 
    method = "rpart")
mean((fit$pred$pred - fit$pred$obs)^2)
## [1] 468.8488

The average MSE value of our k folds is about twice as large as the MSE value we found earlier which suggests a lot of overfitting, which makes sense as you would expect more overfitting when predicting specific numerical values rather than binary data.

Concluding Remarks

From the clustering and classification, I did learn that the state that generally score the highest on the SATs are usually from state that have a lower population, which is also negatively correlated with the amount of pay for teachers. This results in some states with lower pay for teachers to have better SAT scores, which seems counter-intuitive. Furthermore, we found that a logarithmic regression model based on the SAT scores, teacher pay, population, and percent that took SAT will be very good at predicting if a state is rich or not. In conclusion, we uncovered many surprising facts due to this project.
